When other countries try to reduce their economic losses by increasing the cost of goods and commodities, the tariffs are typically the largest.[25] The increased tariffs lead to reduced prices, which can reduce demand for products and services and increase the cost of goods.

A less dramatic difference can be discerned when considering the effects of a policy that is designed to increase the cost of goods and goods. When a country spends more on trade, the tariffs follow a smaller path. When a country has fewer resources to spend on its exports, its demand for more goods and services decreases, or it becomes less expensive to produce goods and services.
